{"title_page": "Slap Fight", "text_new": "{{About|the scrolling shooter arcade game|the form of striking a person|Slapping (disambiguation){{!}}Slap}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{under construction|placedby=KGRAMR|nosection=yes}}\n{{in use}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title         = Slap Fight\n|image         = Slap Fight arcade flyer.jpg\n|caption       = Japanese Arcade flyer\n|developer     ={{collapsible list|title=[[Toaplan]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|[[Probe Software]]<br><small>(CPC/ZX Spectrum)</small><br>[[Imagine Software]] <small>(C64)</small><br>France Image Logiciel<br><small>(Thomson MO5/TO8)</small><br>Abersoft Limited <small>(ST)</small><br>M.N.M Software<br><small>(Mega Drive)</small><ref name=\"EuroGSFMD\">{{cite web|last=Massey|first=Tom|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-05-12-death-from-above-the-making-of-slap-fight-md|title=Death from Above: The making of Slap Fight MD - Mikito Ichikawa takes us behind the doors of a forgotten classic|work=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network Ltd.|date=May 5, 2015|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>}}\n|publisher     ={{collapsible list|title=[[Taito]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|Imagine Software<br><small>(C64/CPC/ST/ZX Spectrum)</small><br>France Image Logiciel<br><small>(Thomson MO5/TO8)</small><br>[[Ocean Software|The Hit Squad]]<br><small>(C64/CPC/ZX Spectrum)</small><br>'''Mega Drive'''{{vgrelease|JP|[[Tengen (company)|Tengen]]|KOR|[[Samsung]]}}}}\n|composer      = Masahiro Yuge\n|platforms     ={{collapsible list|title=[[Arcade game|Arcade]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|[[Amstrad CPC]], [[Atari ST]], [[Commodore 64]], [[Sega Mega Drive]], [[Thomson MO5]], [[Thomson TO8]], [[ZX Spectrum]]}}\n|released      ={{collapsible list|title=[[1986 in video gaming|1986]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|'''Arcade'''{{vgrelease|JP|July 1986<ref name=\"ah1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.arcade-history.com/?n=slap-fight&page=detail&id=2470|title=Slap Fight|website=arcade-history.com|access-date=2019-11-17}}</ref>|NA|December 1986<ref name=\"ah2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.arcade-history.com/?n=alcon&page=detail&id=55|title=Alcon|website=arcade-history.com|access-date=2019-11-17}}</ref>|EU|1986}} '''Amstrad CPC'''{{vgrelease|EU|[[1987 in video gaming|1987]]}} '''Commodore 64'''{{vgrelease|EU|1987|NA|July [[1989 in video gaming|1989]]}} '''Thomson MO5'''{{vgrelease|FRA|1987}} '''Thomson TO8'''{{vgrelease|FRA|1987}} '''ZX Spectrum'''{{vgrelease|EU|1987}} '''Atari ST'''{{vgrelease|EU|[[1988 in video gaming|1988]]|NA|March 1989}} '''Mega Drive'''{{vgrelease|JP|11 June [[1993 in video gaming|1993]]|KOR|1993}}}}\n|genre         = [[Shoot 'em up#Types|Vertically scrolling shooter]]\n|modes         = {{flatlist|\n*[[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n*[[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]}}\n|cabinet       = [[Arcade cabinet#Upright cabinets|Upright]]\n|arcade system = Toaplan Slap Fight<ref name=\"s16\">{{cite web|url=http://www.system16.com/hardware.php?id=643&page=1#1567|title=Toaplan Slapfight Hardware (Other)|website=system16.com|accessdate=2019-11-17}}</ref>\n|cpu           = (2x) [[Zilog Z80|Z80]] (@ 6 [[MHz]]),<br>[[Motorola 68705|M68705]] (@ 1 MHz)<ref name=\"ah1\"/><ref name=\"s16\"/>\n|sound         = (2x) [[General Instrument AY-3-8910|GI AY-3-8910]] (@ 1.5 MHz)<ref name=\"ah1\"/><ref name=\"s16\"/>\n|display       = [[Raster graphics|Raster]], 240 x 280 pixels (Vertical), 256 [[color]]s\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''''Slap Fight'''''|\u30b9\u30e9\u30c3\u30d7\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30c8}}, also known as '''''Alcon''''', is a [[1986 in video gaming|1986]] vertically [[Shoot 'em up#Scrolling shooters|scrolling shooter]] [[arcade game]] developed by [[Toaplan]] and published by [[Taito]].\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[File:ARC Slap Fight (Alcon).png|thumb|left|Arcade version screenshot.]]\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\nIt takes its inspiration from ''[[Xevious]]'' (being a vertical scroller) and ''[[Gradius]]'' (from which it borrows its [[power-up]] system), and helps to establish Toaplan's trademark style. The game takes place in an Earth-type environment with metallic, land-based enemies; some are mobile armor and others are fortifications embedded in natural terrain.\n\nCertain enemies leave power-up stars upon destruction. Collecting these stars \"turns on\" an upgrade menu at the bottom of the screen and moves a lit cursor through the list of power-ups described below. If any power-up is lit, but a ship is lost before a power-up could be selected, the star is \"carried over\" and the Speed block is lit on the next life. Single hits to the unshielded main ship destroy it, and the player loses any accumulated upgrades including Speed. This can make successive lives difficult to keep in the heat of battle.\n\nThis game does not support [[continue (video gaming)|continue]]s with extra credits, and is believed to \"loop\" endlessly; that is, after the final boss, gameplay resumes at the beginning of the play map but at successively higher difficulty, with enemies shooting faster and more frequently. Also, the score stops increasing when it displays 9,999,990 points, which might be achieved as early as the 15th, 16th, or 17th loops ([http://replay.marpirc.net/r/slapfighb1 beginning of 17th verified via MAME]).\n\n=== Power-ups ===\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\nPower-ups appearing on the upgrade menu are somewhat similar to those in ''Gradius'':\n\n* Speed (upgradeable five times cumulatively)\n* Side-Shot (rapid-fire assistant; remains with ship regardless of main weapon unless/until ship is destroyed)\n* Shot (short-range, rapid-fire)\n* Wing (accessory; increases both the width and the exposure of the craft; improves the power or speed of equipped weapon; upgradeable to three pairs; two external pairs can be used to absorb hits but the whole pair will be lost)\n* Bomb (short-range, slow fire, area effect)\n* Laser (long-range)\n* Homing Missile (releases up to sixteen guided missiles) \n* Shield (invulnerability; lasts approx. 25 seconds, or 3 hits, whichever comes first; ends with audible warning)\n\nThe major weapons affect the enemies and terrain differently. For example, certain enemy towers can only be destroyed with Laser or Homing Missile; other enemies are destroyed ''much faster'' with specific weapons to match. If Bomb or Homing Missile are equipped, certain bonus targets will appear, or parts of the landscape may be destroyed to reveal bonuses. If Laser is active, certain plants in the landscape can be shot repeatedly to 'grow' and earn extra points until they scroll off-screen.\nIt has been reported that a bug in the game enabled the player to obtain all power-ups, simply by allowing themselves to be killed by the first enemy appearing upon starting the game without touching the controls. If this occurred, the next time the player ship appears, it has all the power-ups equipped.[http://www.rllmukforum.com/index.php?/topic/76529-best-trick-cheat-or-bug-in-an-arcade-game/page-2 Slap Fight bug]\n\n== Synopsis ==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\nTaking place in the year 2059 in another galaxy, mankind has colonized an alien planet called Theon after evacuating a previously colonized planet Orac. Five years ago, the colony on Orac was attacked by alien invaders and the war was so intense, the colonists were forced to leave. However, Theon is now under attack by the same alien fleet, but the humans are ready. The player assumes the role of an Allied League of Cosmic Nations (ALCON) fighter pilot in the SW475 star fighter to stop the invaders from taking over Theon.\n\n== Development ==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Release ==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\nThe game was [[porting|ported]] to many 8-bit [[home computer]]s in the European & North American markets.\n\n''Slap Fight MD'' itself is a new game mode featuring featured new levels, graphics, weapons, music, etc., plus a new \"smart bomb\" feature at the cost of Wing powerups. The music for it was composed and arranged by [[Yuzo Koshiro]], which is presented on the title screen.\n\nThe original game was also included, but with changes such as configuration for the Shield's timer and an in-game announcer.\n\n=== Taito Nostalgia 2 version ===\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\nIn ''Taito Nostalgia 2'' for Bandai's \"Let's! TV play CLASSIC\" series of plug-and-play game systems, the original Japanese version and a new ''Slap Fight Tiger'' are included.\n\nIn ''Slap Fight Tiger'', the player controls the Heli from ''[[Tiger Heli]]'' instead of the SW475. The laser is changed to fire in a 3-way forward spread. New enemies include the Invaders Army (from ''[[Space Invaders]]'').<ref>[http://archive.tamashii.jp/lyvp/play/t2slap2.html Taito Nostalgia 2 Slap Fight Tiger page] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130612113055/http://archive.tamashii.jp/lyvp/play/t2slap2.html |date=2013-06-12 }}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{moby game|id=/alcon|name=''Slap Fight''}}\n*[http://klov.com/game_detail.php?letter=&game_id=9583 ''Slap Fight'' entry] and also related [http://www.klov.com/game_detail.php?game_id=6843 ''Alcon'' entry] from the [[Killer List of Videogames|KLOV]]\n*{{WoS game|id=0004564}}\n\n{{Toaplan video games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Slap Fight}}\n[[Category:1986 video games]]\n[[Category:Amstrad CPC games]]\n[[Category:Arcade games]]\n[[Category:Atari ST games]]\n[[Category:Commodore 64 games]]\n[[Category:Scrolling shooters]]\n[[Category:Sega Genesis games]]\n[[Category:Sega Genesis-only games]]\n[[Category:Toaplan games]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Martin Galway]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Yuzo Koshiro]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the 2050s]]\n[[Category:ZX Spectrum games]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the scrolling shooter arcade game|the form of striking a person|Slapping (disambiguation){{!}}Slap}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{under construction|placedby=KGRAMR|nosection=yes}}\n{{in use}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title         = Slap Fight\n|image         = Slap Fight arcade flyer.jpg\n|caption       = Japanese Arcade flyer\n|developer     ={{collapsible list|title=[[Toaplan]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|[[Probe Software]]<br><small>(CPC/ZX Spectrum)</small><br>[[Imagine Software]] <small>(C64)</small><br>France Image Logiciel<br><small>(Thomson MO5/TO8)</small><br>Abersoft Limited <small>(ST)</small><br>M.N.M Software<br><small>(Mega Drive)</small><ref name=\"EuroGSFMD\">{{cite web|last=Massey|first=Tom|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-05-12-death-from-above-the-making-of-slap-fight-md|title=Death from Above: The making of Slap Fight MD - Mikito Ichikawa takes us behind the doors of a forgotten classic|work=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network Ltd.|date=May 5, 2015|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>}}\n|publisher     ={{collapsible list|title=[[Taito]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|Imagine Software<br><small>(C64/CPC/ST/ZX Spectrum)</small><br>France Image Logiciel<br><small>(Thomson MO5/TO8)</small><br>[[Ocean Software|The Hit Squad]]<br><small>(C64/CPC/ZX Spectrum)</small><br>'''Mega Drive'''{{vgrelease|JP|[[Tengen (company)|Tengen]]|KOR|[[Samsung]]}}}}\n|composer      = Masahiro Yuge\n|platforms     ={{collapsible list|title=[[Arcade game|Arcade]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|[[Amstrad CPC]], [[Atari ST]], [[Commodore 64]], [[Sega Mega Drive]], [[Thomson MO5]], [[Thomson TO8]], [[ZX Spectrum]]}}\n|released      ={{collapsible list|title=[[1986 in video gaming|1986]]